<% content_for :title, "erbswap — server-driven UI for Rails in under 200 lines" %>

<section class="intro">
  <h2 class="intro__title">Server-driven UI for Rails, without a framework.</h2>

  <p class="lead">
    <strong>erbswap</strong> is a thin pattern: a Rails controller concern and
    just under 200 lines of vanilla JavaScript. Your server renders plain ERB
    partials. The browser does <code>fetch</code> + DOM swap. That's the whole
    thing.
  </p>

  <p>
    Zero dependencies. Zero build step. No <code>npm</code>, no <code>hx-*</code>
    attributes, no <code>&lt;turbo-frame&gt;</code> custom element. Same family
    as HTMX, Turbo, and Phoenix LiveView &mdash; deliberately the smallest
    possible thing in that family. The point is restraint: a starting point
    with a clear upgrade path the moment you outgrow it.
  </p>

  <div class="intro__cta">
    <a href="https://github.com/erbswap/erbswap" class="button">Source on GitHub</a>
    <%= link_to "Try the examples →", examples_tasks_path, class: "button button--ghost" %>
  </div>

  <p class="intro__notice">
    <strong>Heads up:</strong> this demo runs on Render's free tier. After a
    few minutes of inactivity the server sleeps, so the first request takes
    ~30 seconds while it spins back up. Once awake it's responsive.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="how-to-use">
  <h2 class="how-to-use__title">How to use</h2>
  <p class="how-to-use__intro">
    Two files, two include lines, a working swap in four steps.
  </p>

  <div class="step">
    <div class="step__number">1</div>
    <div class="step__body">
      <h3>Copy two files into your Rails app</h3>
      <ul class="step__files">
        <li><code>app/javascript/erbswap.js</code> &mdash; the library (under 200 lines, zero dependencies)</li>
        <li><code>app/controllers/concerns/erbswap_renderable.rb</code> &mdash; one private method</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="step">
    <div class="step__number">2</div>
    <div class="step__body">
      <h3>Wire them up</h3>
      <pre><code><%= @step2_code %></code></pre>
      <p class="step__note">
        On Sprockets use <code>//= require erbswap</code> instead. Or drop the
        file in a plain <code>&lt;script&gt;</code> tag &mdash; it self-registers.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="step">
    <div class="step__number">3</div>
    <div class="step__body">
      <h3>Write your first swap</h3>
      <p>Five small pieces. Paste them into your app and you have a working swap.</p>
      <pre><code><%= @step3_code %></code></pre>
      <p class="step__note">
        Visit <code>/widgets</code> &rarr; click <em>Submit</em> &rarr;
        <em>It worked.</em> swaps in. No page reload.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="step">
    <div class="step__number">4</div>
    <div class="step__body">
      <h3>Write down the four invariants</h3>
      <p>
        Put these in your <code>CLAUDE.md</code> / <code>README</code> / <code>ARCHITECTURE.md</code>.
        Without an explicit ceiling, this library grows into a 1,000-line
        home-built framework &mdash; the exact trap it exists to avoid.
      </p>
      <ol class="step__invariants">
        <li><strong>Same frame id, every state.</strong> The wrapper <code>&lt;div id="..."&gt;</code> is identical across initial / success / empty / error partials.</li>
        <li><strong>Two swap modes only.</strong> <code>innerHTML</code> and <code>replace</code>. No positional swap, no <code>beforeend</code>.</li>
        <li><strong>Single controller entry point.</strong> <code>render_erbswap(partial:, locals:, status:)</code>. No second helper, no JSON envelope.</li>
        <li><strong>Out of scope.</strong> Out-of-band swap, history push, SSE, retry, abort. When you need these, move to HTMX or Turbo.</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="next">
  <p>
    Full reference, FAQ, and comparison with HTMX / Turbo / LiveView in the
